\section{A framework for sustainaiblity thinking}%Impacts and their sources}
Two mathematical identities, IPAT and Kaya, have been used to express sources and impact
of human activities on the environment.
IPAT expresses ``impact'' ($I$) on the environment as the product of human
population ($P$), affluence ($A$), and technology ($T$).
The Kaya identity is a form of the IPAT equation but restricts impact to CO$_2$
emissions.
On the other hand, Kaya expands the generic expression for ``technology'' to be
the product of energy intensity of the economy (units of energy per GDP)
and the carbon intensity of energy (units of CO$_2$ per unit energy).

Chapters \ref{chap:planetary_boundaries}-\ref{chap:carbon_intensity}
of this book are organized around a hybrid of the IPAT and Kaya
approaches.
We keep the more general ``impact'' of IPAT but also generalize the more insightful
``technology'' expression from Kaya as the product of resource intensity of the economy ($R$)
and the contamination intensity of resources ($C$).

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:IPARC}
\small
\begin{tabular}{ccccccccc}
$I$    & = & $P$        & $\times$ & $A$       & $\times$ & $R$      & $\times$ & $X$ \\
\multirow{2}{*}{Impact} &  & \multirow{2}{*}{Population} &  & \multirow{2}{*}{Affluence} &  & Resource &  & Impact intensity \\
 &  &  &  &  &  & intensity &  & of resources \\
$\left[\frac{\textrm{impact}}{\textrm{year}}\right]$ & & $\left[\mathrm{persons}\right]$ &  & $\left[\frac{\textrm{GDP}}{\textrm{capita-year}}\right]$ &  & $\left[\frac{\textrm{resources}}{\textrm{GDP}}\right]$ &  & $\left[\frac{\textrm{impact}}{\textrm{resources}}\right]$
\end{tabular}
\normalsize
\end{equation}


In the IPARC formulation, impact ($I$) is a list of impacts (that is, a vector quantity)
that includes such things as global warming potential, aquifer depletion, and
eutrophication potential.
Population ($P$) is the number of people in the world.
Affluence ($A$) is GDP per capita per year.
Resource intensity ($R$) is the list (vector) of all the resources necessary to
produce one unit of world GDP.
Lastly, impact intensity of resources ($X$) is a list of the impacts of
each type of resource. (That is, $X$ is a matrix quantity.)

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
The IPARC identity is a static relationship.
Its terms represent steady-state levels,
but do not necessarily show how changes in any one variable will affect the others.
For instance, using resources more efficiently (improving resource intensity),
does not, in general, lower impact.
Instead, it leads to more affluence (see chapter \ref{chap:resource_intensity}).
Likewise, it may not be possible to drive the impact(s) per unit of resource to
zero because of diminishing returns on efficiency 
and tradeoffs that exist between different types of impacts.
Thus, while Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} is useful as a conceptual framework for 
thinking about sustainability challenges, it does \emph{not} provide a roadmap for
sustainability solutions.
\end{mcframe}

IPARC is true because it is an identity, and it provides a useful organizing framework
for the following chapters.
To illustrate the IPARC framework, energy and CO$_2$ are prime examples
in the rest of the text because energy is the master resource
% Need "energy is the master resource section??!
and climate change is our most urgent sustainability challenge, and, of course,
the two are closely linked.

\section{The mathematics of sustainability}
\label{sec:exp}
Returning to the grain and chessboard problem, for a series of doubling numbers, like the
number of grains on a chessboard's squares: $1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, …$, the sum of all the
numbers in the series is always one less than the next number in the series.
For example, $1+2+4+8 = 15$, which is one less than $16$ and $1+2+4+8+16 = 31$,
which is one less than $32$.
Thus, the amount of grain in the next square is always greater than the sum total
of all the grain on all previous squares.
The formula for the total grain on $N$ squares is $2^N-1$.
The amount of grain on the $N^\text{th}$ square is $2^{N-1}$, which is half of $2^N$,
and so is one more than the sum of all previous $N-1$ squares.

Doubling on discrete squares (or in discrete time units) can be extended to 
continuous time. 
Exponential growth is growth at a \emph{constant rate} (in percent per year), 
which means doubling in a fixed amount of time.
That is, the time it takes to double does not depend on the amount there is at
the current moment. 
If the (constant) rate of growth is $r$, then amount of time to double is $ln(2)/r$, 
which is approximately 70 divided by the growth rate, 
when the growth rate is expressed as a percentage.
For example, With a fixed 3\%/yr growth rate, GDP doubles every 23 years.
If your investment portfolio has a 7\%/yr return, your wealth will double
every 10 years.
Or, as shown in Figure~\ref{fig:exp}, $y$ doubles from $1$ to $2$ to $4$ to $8$ 
to $16$ every $6.93$ years.

