In the discrete case, like grain on a chessboard, the number of grains on the
next square is always one more than the sum of all the previous squares.
In the continuous case, the area under the curve between ``now'' and the next
doubling is more than the sum of all previous areas.
Thus, in Figure~\ref{fig:exp}, the yellow area has a value of $10$, the blue
area has a value of $20$, the purple area has a value of $40$, and the green 
area has a value of $80$.
Purple is more than blue plus yellow and green is more than purple plus blue plus yellow.

If the line in Figure~\ref{fig:exp} represents population or GDP, then the area
under the line represents the resources needed to support that activity.
For instance, the area could represent the amount of food necessary to feed the 
population.
(People eat an approximately constant amount of food per time, 
see Chapter~\ref{chap:agriculture}.
The various resources needed by the economy to produce a unit of GDP may be assumed
to be constant over a short period of time but are not constant long term, 
see Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}.)

Population (P) and affluence (A) in Equation \ref{eq:IPARC} \emph{have} been growing
exponentially. 
Chapter \ref{chap:population} gives us some hope that population won't keep growing 
exponentially.
(In fact, there are some indications world population may \emph{fall} after a peak
in the mid-twenty-first century.)
However, world economies are \emph{actively managed} to have a continual growth 
(say a target of 3\% GDP growth per year).
The implication for sustainability is that the resources – for instance, the energy –
needed by the economy in the next 23 years will be more than the total
resources (energy) used in all of history to date.
(Improvements in energy efficiency over time will tend to spur further economic growth 
rather than provide economic growth with zero resource cost;
efficiency improvements are subject to diminishing returns, 
see Figure~\ref{fig:E_vs_GDP_graph}.)
Because of this exponential growth, resource use goes to infinity on a finite planet.
Humanity is not on a sustainable path.

