\section{Energy is the master resource}
\label{sec:masterE}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Energy is the ultimate or master resource. 
Obtaining and using any other resource requires energy. 
Collecting firewood to heat houses requires energy. 
Extracting crude oil requires energy. 
Harvesting food requires energy. 
Making solar panels ... you guessed it, requires energy.

Energy is also the master resource because resources can be converted into other
types of resources with energy. 
Crude oil can be refined to gasoline.
Corn can be converted to ethanol.
Salt water can be converted to fresh water. 
Petroleum or natural gas can be converted to pharmaceuticals or plastics.

Finally, energy is needed to break down or dispose of wastes. 
Building a landfill takes energy.
Hauling garbage to the landfill takes energy.
Even the decomposition of compost takes sunlight, air, and rain.

The amount of energy delivered to the economy as a fraction of the energy it took to deliver that energy 
is called the energy return on investment (EROI).

\begin{equation}\label{eroi}
   EROI = \frac{\mathrm{Useful \; energy \; delivered \; to \; society}}
               {\mathrm{Energy \; required \; to \; obtain \; delivered \; energy}}
\end{equation}

An EROI that is less than one indicates the energy production activity is an energy \emph{sink}
rather than an energy \emph{source}.
For instance, modern agriculture has an EROI of around 0.15 to 0.1; 
it takes 7-10 calories of energy to deliver 1 calorie of food energy.
On the other hand, an EROI greater than one indicates a source of useful energy.
Table \ref{tab:eroi} lists energy returns for various sources of energy.
Some authors have suggested a minimum EROI of 5 for sustainability \cite{Ferruccio2016}
with 12 to 13 necessary for a technological society.

